    "**Dataset:** Experience vs Salary (1000 samples)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 馃搶 Project Overview\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook builds a **univariate linear regression** model to predict salaries from years of experience 鈥� a classic, well-suited problem for regression because:\n",
    "\n",
    "- There is a single, continuous input feature (experience in months)\n",
    "- The target (salary) is continuous and numeric\n",
    "- The relationship is expected to be approximately linear\n",
    "\n",
    "We follow a complete end-to-end ML workflow:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Stage | What we do |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| 1. Setup | Import libraries |\n",
    "| 2. Data Loading | Load CSV, inspect shape and types |\n",
    "| 3. EDA | Scatter plots, distributions, correlation |\n",
    "| 4. Preprocessing | Define X/y, train-test split |\n",
    "| 5. Modelling | Linear, Ridge, and Lasso regression |\n",
    "| 6. Evaluation | MSE, RMSE, MAE, R虏, cross-validation |\n",
    "| 7. Visualization | Regression line, Actual vs Predicted, Residuals |\n",
    "| 8. Prediction | Infer salary for new experience values |\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 馃摎 Concepts You Will Learn\n",
    "- **Ordinary Least Squares (OLS):** How `sklearn` fits the best-fit line by minimizing the sum of squared residuals.\n",
    "- **Bias-Variance Tradeoff:** Why train vs. test metrics may differ.\n",
    "- **Regularization:** What Ridge (L2) and Lasso (L1) do, and when they actually help.\n",
    "- **Evaluation Metrics:** How to read MSE, RMSE, MAE, and R虏 鈥� and what they tell you about model quality.\n",
    "- **Residual Analysis:** How to verify your model assumptions (linearity, normality, homoscedasticity)."
   ]
  },
