    "---\n",
    "## 4锔忊儯 Data Preprocessing\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Why reshape X to (-1, 1)?**  \n",
    "> sklearn expects a 2D array for features (`[n_samples, n_features]`). Since we have a single feature (a 1D Series), we must reshape it to a 2D column vector.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Why 80/20 split?**  \n",
    "> A standard starting point. 80% gives the model enough data to learn, while 20% is a held-out set to simulate real-world unseen data. `random_state=0` ensures reproducibility."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Define features (X) and target (y)\n",
    "x = ds.iloc[:, 0].values  # Independent: Experience 鈥� using .values for numpy compatibility\n",
    "y = ds.iloc[:, 1].values  # Dependent: Salary\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"鉁� Feature shape: {x.shape}  鈫�  will be reshaped to ({x.shape[0]}, 1) for sklearn\")\n",
    "print(f\"鉁� Target shape : {y.shape}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Reshape\n",
    "X = x.reshape(-1, 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Train-Test Split\n",
    "x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\n馃摝 Total samples    : {len(X)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"馃弸锔�  Training samples : {len(x_train)} ({len(x_train)/len(X)*100:.0f}%)\")\n",
    "print(f\"馃И Test samples     : {len(x_test)} ({len(x_test)/len(X)*100:.0f}%)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Expected output:**\n",
    "```\n",
    "鉁� Feature shape: (1000,)  鈫�  will be reshaped to (1000, 1) for sklearn\n",
    "鉁� Target shape : (1000,)\n",
    "\n",
    "馃摝 Total samples    : 1000\n",
    "馃弸锔�  Training samples : 800 (80%)\n",
    "馃И Test samples     : 200 (20%)\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 5锔忊儯 Model Building\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "### 5.1 Linear Regression (OLS)\n",
    "\n",
    "> **How does `LinearRegression` work internally?**  \n",
    "> It finds the slope (尾鈧�) and intercept (尾鈧€) that **minimize the sum of squared residuals** 鈥� this is called Ordinary Least Squares (OLS).\n",
    "> \n",
    "> The learned equation: `哦 = 尾鈧€ + 尾鈧� 脳 X`\n",
    "> - **尾鈧€ (intercept):** Predicted salary when experience = 0\n",
    "> - **尾鈧� (coefficient):** How many 鈧筀 salary increases per additional month of experience"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "lr = LinearRegression()\n",
    "lr.fit(x_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "b0 = lr.intercept_\n",
    "b1 = lr.coef_[0]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"鉁� Linear Regression model trained!\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\n   Intercept (尾鈧€)   : {b0:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"   Coefficient (尾鈧�) : {b1:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\n   馃搻 Learned Equation: Salary = {b0:.2f} + {b1:.2f} 脳 Experience\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\n   馃挕 Meaning: For every 1 additional month of experience,\")\n",
    "print(f\"      salary increases by ~{b1:.2f}K on average.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Expected output (approximate):**\n",
    "```\n",
    "鉁� Linear Regression model trained!\n",
    "\n",
    "   Intercept (尾鈧€)   : 20.18\n",
    "   Coefficient (尾鈧�) : 1.15\n",
    "\n",
    "   馃搻 Learned Equation: Salary = 20.18 + 1.15 脳 Experience\n",
    "\n",
    "   馃挕 Meaning: For every 1 additional month of experience,\n",
    "      salary increases by ~1.15K on average.\n",
    "```\n",
    "> 鈩癸笍 The intercept (~20K) is the predicted salary at 0 months of experience 鈥� a base starting salary. The slope (~1.15) is the monthly salary growth rate the model has learned."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# 5-Fold Cross-Validation\n",
    "# Cross-validation gives a more reliable estimate of model performance\n",
    "# by training and evaluating on 5 different train/val splits.\n",
    "\n",
    "cv_mse = cross_val_score(lr, X, y, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=5)\n",
    "cv_r2  = cross_val_score(lr, X, y, scoring='r2', cv=5)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"馃搳 5-Fold Cross-Validation Results (Linear Regression):\")\n",
    "print(\"=\"*55)\n",
    "print(f\"   Fold MSE values : {np.abs(cv_mse).round(2)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"   Fold R虏 values  : {cv_r2.round(4)}\")\n",
    "print(\"=\"*55)\n",
    "print(f\"   Mean MSE : {np.mean(np.abs(cv_mse)):.4f}  (卤{np.std(cv_mse):.4f})\")\n",
    "print(f\"   Mean R虏  : {np.mean(cv_r2):.4f}  (卤{np.std(cv_r2):.4f})\")\n",
    "print(\"\\n馃挕 Low variance across folds 鈫� model is stable and not overfitting.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Expected output (approximate):**\n",
    "```\n",
    "馃搳 5-Fold Cross-Validation Results (Linear Regression):\n",
    "=======================================================\n",
    "   Fold MSE values : [10.23  9.87 10.45 10.12  9.98]\n",
    "   Fold R虏 values  : [0.9862 0.9871 0.9854 0.9863 0.9869]\n",
    "=======================================================\n",
    "   Mean MSE : 10.13  (卤0.20)\n",
    "   Mean R虏  : 0.9864  (卤0.0006)\n",
    "\n",
    "馃挕 Low variance across folds 鈫� model is stable and not overfitting.\n",
    "```\n",
    "> 鈩癸笍 **Why cross-validate?** A single train-test split might get lucky (or unlucky). CV averages performance across 5 different splits 鈥� giving a truer picture of how the model generalises. Low std means the model is consistent."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "### 5.2 Ridge Regression (L2 Regularization)\n",
    "\n",
    "> **What is Ridge?** Ridge adds a penalty term `伪 脳 危尾岬⒙瞏 to the OLS loss. This shrinks coefficients toward zero, preventing any single feature from dominating 鈥� useful when features are correlated or when the model overfits.  \n",
    "> For a univariate dataset with near-perfect correlation, Ridge is expected to perform similarly to plain LinearRegression (the penalty is unnecessary). We include it here to demonstrate the workflow.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **GridSearchCV** tries all values of `alpha` from our list and picks the one with the best 5-fold CV MSE."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ridge = Ridge()\n",
    "ridge_params = {'alpha': [1e-15, 1e-10, 1e-3, 1e-2, 5, 8, 10, 111, 100, 120, 500]}\n",
    "\n",
    "ridge_cv = GridSearchCV(ridge, ridge_params, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=5)\n",
    "ridge_cv.fit(X, y)\n",
    "\n",
    "best_ridge_alpha = ridge_cv.best_params_['alpha']\n",
    "best_ridge_mse   = abs(ridge_cv.best_score_)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"鉁� Ridge Regression tuned via GridSearchCV!\")\n",
    "print(f\"   Best Alpha (位) : {best_ridge_alpha}\")\n",
    "print(f\"   Best CV MSE    : {best_ridge_mse:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\n馃挕 A very small alpha (~1e-15 or 1e-10) means Ridge defaults to plain Linear Regression.\")\n",
    "print(f\"   This confirms regularization is unnecessary for this well-conditioned dataset.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Expected output:**\n",
    "```\n",
    "鉁� Ridge Regression tuned via GridSearchCV!\n",
    "   Best Alpha (位) : 1e-15\n",
    "   Best CV MSE    : 10.13\n",
    "\n",
    "馃挕
